  "slug": "almond-croissants-leftover",
  "title": "Almond croissants from day-old croissants",
  "subtitle": "Soaked, filled, and baked a second time with almond cream",
  "excerpt": "Day-old croissants soaked in a rum syrup, split and filled with almond cream, then baked again with flaked almonds scattered on top. The second bake puffs the filling and crisps the almonds, and the croissants come out softer and richer than fresh ones. Makes twelve.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "The classical French method of double-baking day-old croissants soaked in syrup and filled with frangipane is documented across pre-1928 French sources as a Parisian household economy. Marie-Antoine Carême and Henri-Paul Pellaprat both note the practice as a way of reusing yesterday's bake. Modern bakery shops use the same method.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "These are yesterday's croissants made into something better. You soak day-old plain croissants in a sweet rum or vanilla syrup, split them, spread almond cream inside and on top, scatter flaked almonds, and bake them a second time. The second bake puffs the filling and crisps the almonds, and the croissants come out gold and softer than fresh ones. Makes twelve, about 40 minutes of work plus 18 minutes in the oven.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Day-old shop-bought croissants work as well as homemade ones. The recipe pairs well with the laminated-croissants tutorial: bake a batch on Saturday, turn the leftovers into these on Sunday.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
